<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-321-896  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 321 896.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  June 5 1989 n420 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software lobby pushes congress on copyright. (unauthorized copyingof software)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Stacey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The software industry is pressuring Congress to amend the UScopyright law in order to stop unauthorized duplication ofsoftware by state governments and universities.andP;  Softwarecompanies cannot bring damage suits against states that violatecopyrights because the 11th Amendment of the US Constitutionprohibits states from being sued for damages in federal courts,which have exclusive jurisdiction over copyright law.andP;  Thesecourts can only issue injunctions that prohibit further copying bystates, but with no compensation for past duplication.andP;  Thesoftware industry feels that the threat of such an injunction isnot strong enough to motivate states from violating copyrightlaws.andP;  The software industry is now asking that a statementsubjecting states to damage suits in federal court be added to thecopyright law.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software PublishersSoftware ProtectionLegal IssuesCopyrightLaw EnforcementColleges and UniversitiesState Government.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>